# Security Operations Center (SOC) Incident Response Workflow Engineering

## Overview
This laboratory documentation details the deployment and configuration of an enterprise-grade incident response lifecycle within an isolated virtual sandbox. By integrating the Znuny (OTRS) ticketing framework with centralized system logic, this deployment models a structured, multi-tier Security Operations Center (SOC) capable of ingesting, triaging, and tracking security incidents against defined Service Level Agreements (SLAs). 

The primary objective of this lab is to move beyond passive log visibility and implement a repeatable, auditable defensive workflow for enterprise incident tracking.

---

## Environment Architecture and Prerequisites
The infrastructure is built upon a virtualized environment utilizing VMware with network adapters provisioned in NAT mode to maintain secure execution parameters. 

### System Initialization
The core system relies on specific background processes to handle mail processing, database tasks, and scheduled workflows. The following processes must be started sequentially within the /opt/otrs/ directory:

```bash
# Navigate to the application root directory
cd /opt/otrs/

# Start the background task daemon under the otrs system user
su -c "bin/otrs.Daemon.pl start" -s /bin/bash otrs

# Initialize the automated system cron scheduler
su -c "bin/Cron.sh start" -s /bin/bash otrs

# Launch MailHog to serve as the local SMTP testing engine
mailhog
```


*Figure 1: Initializing background daemons and local SMTP email traps.*

### Local DNS Resolution
To replicate enterprise network routing, local host file manipulation was performed on the host operating system (C:\Windows\System32\drivers\etc\hosts). This maps the Linux appliance IP address directly to a fully qualified domain name (FQDN), enabling seamless browser routing:

```text
208.8.8.146    socir.ticket.com
```


