## Defensive Queue Architecture and SLA Matrix
The system employs a strict tier-isolated defensive model. Incidents are systematically routed through distinct queues based on complexity, handling constraints, and investigative depth. 

Each tier is bound by enforceable Service Level Agreements (SLAs) to guarantee operational efficiency and track metrics like Time-to-Acknowledge (TTA) and Time-to-Remediate (TTR).

| Operational Queue | Core Responsibility | First Response Target | Update Windows | Resolution SLA |
| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| L1 – Alert Analyst | Frontline monitoring, initial alert triage, and false-positive filtering. | 15 Minutes | 15 Minutes | 60 Minutes |
| Tier 2 – Incident Responder | Deep-dive logs investigation, host isolation, and active threat containment. | 15 Minutes | 15 Minutes | 60 Minutes |
| L3 – Threat Hunter / Forensics | Advanced malware analysis, root-cause identification, and hunting exercises. | 15 Minutes | 15 Minutes | 60 Minutes |


